Q40: 2 or 3 days before the deadline. This time frame allows me to plan a few days ahead time if I hadn't already made plans to complete PCRS. Q49: I think it may be helpful to break up the prompts? Such as: / - What is something that seems wrong in each of these code examples? / Then if the student still doesn't answer, then follow up with: / - What is something that is correct in each of these code examples? /  /  / I'm not sure if this would actually help? But how I feel about the prompts is that when you ask the student to answer both right and wrong about each of the prompts it can seem overwhelming to do, especially for a m/c question that isn't necessarily supposed to take a long time. However, it is important to think about these questions when a student is in the learning process, so that is why I broke up the one prompt into two prompts. The first question gets the student narrow down the choices.  The second question asks the student is the code example doing what it is supposed to be doing? /  / I'm not sure if the ordering of the prompts is the best ordering, but I would rather see the prompt be broken down into two because having to do so much just for one questions seems too tedious.

Q40: It would be helpful to get prompts that are spanned throughout similar length (every nth day for example). Lecture and PCRS should tie in (as planned), but without this consistency it is easy to fall behind without noticing.

Q49: I think it may be helpful to break up the prompts? Such as: / - What is something that seems wrong in each of these code examples? / Then if the student still doesn't answer, then follow up with: / - What is something that is correct in each of these code examples? /  /  / I'm not sure if this would actually help? But how I feel about the prompts is that when you ask the student to answer both right and wrong about each of the prompts it can seem overwhelming to do, especially for a m/c question that isn't necessarily supposed to take a long time. However, it is important to think about these questions when a student is in the learning process, so that is why I broke up the one prompt into two prompts. The first question gets the student narrow down the choices.  The second question asks the student is the code example doing what it is supposed to be doing? /  / I'm not sure if the ordering of the prompts is the best ordering, but I would rather see the prompt be broken down into two because having to do so much just for one questions seems too tedious.

One exception is the "one great way to learn more is to stop and think!" prompt. / That prompt is worse than useless - it is annoying... / It takes my attention away from the course material and that is not productive. /  / Talk about "learning more" is vague and pointless. How do you quantify how well someone learns something? If it's quality, then you can't even put that into words to begin with, so why bother? / I think your attention is in the wrong place when you start off asking a question like that... /  / Taking a pause to think about what led a student to their answer is indeed a good prompt to give, it just needs to be worded in a more specific, useful, and deliberate way.

Q84: Because it is what I observed in the Bubble sort video and based on the algorithm. I used the fact that a single pass terminates when the comparisons reach the far right of the list, where the item being compared may or may not reach the end if it is or isn't the biggest. But, because it pushes anything smaller behind it, and something bigger replaces it in the comparisons if needed, the last item is always going to be the biggest.

Q49: I think it may be helpful to break up the prompts? Such as: / - What is something that seems wrong in each of these code examples? / Then if the student still doesn't answer, then follow up with: / - What is something that is correct in each of these code examples? /  /  / I'm not sure if this would actually help? But how I feel about the prompts is that when you ask the student to answer both right and wrong about each of the prompts it can seem overwhelming to do, especially for a m/c question that isn't necessarily supposed to take a long time. However, it is important to think about these questions when a student is in the learning process, so that is why I broke up the one prompt into two prompts. The first question gets the student narrow down the choices.  The second question asks the student is the code example doing what it is supposed to be doing? /  / I'm not sure if the ordering of the prompts is the best ordering, but I would rather see the prompt be broken down into two because having to do so much just for one questions seems too tedious.

Q114.1: Get students to explain what led them to their answer/explain their answer. That will already get them to reflect. After they get asked that by a prof and it throws them off, they will respond afterwards in one of two ways: (a) they will remember this experience and reflect on their own time without prompt to ensure they do not embarass themselves again, or (b) they will get annoyed and avoid talking to the prof from then onwards - to avoid landing back into that uncomfortable position.

Q49: I think it may be helpful to break up the prompts? Such as: / - What is something that seems wrong in each of these code examples? / Then if the student still doesn't answer, then follow up with: / - What is something that is correct in each of these code examples? /  /  / I'm not sure if this would actually help? But how I feel about the prompts is that when you ask the student to answer both right and wrong about each of the prompts it can seem overwhelming to do, especially for a m/c question that isn't necessarily supposed to take a long time. However, it is important to think about these questions when a student is in the learning process, so that is why I broke up the one prompt into two prompts. The first question gets the student narrow down the choices.  The second question asks the student is the code example doing what it is supposed to be doing? /  / I'm not sure if the ordering of the prompts is the best ordering, but I would rather see the prompt be broken down into two because having to do so much just for one questions seems too tedious.

Q47: Some of these prompts give me examples to consider, which is helpful. Moreover, prompts that ask me about why one code might fail while another succeeds encourages me to read the code from start to finish in an attempt to assess the code's validity, which might also help me with my own code if there is a line of code that achieves a task I want that I may not know how to write.
Q48: Some of these are not helpful, specifically the ones that ask to explain the answers you've given because they don't provide any explanation as to what we should be talking about as in should we focus on the concepts or the specific syntax.
Q49: I think it may be helpful to break up the prompts? Such as: / - What is something that seems wrong in each of these code examples? / Then if the student still doesn't answer, then follow up with: / - What is something that is correct in each of these code examples? /  /  / I'm not sure if this would actually help? But how I feel about the prompts is that when you ask the student to answer both right and wrong about each of the prompts it can seem overwhelming to do, especially for a m/c question that isn't necessarily supposed to take a long time. However, it is important to think about these questions when a student is in the learning process, so that is why I broke up the one prompt into two prompts. The first question gets the student narrow down the choices.  The second question asks the student is the code example doing what it is supposed to be doing? /  / I'm not sure if the ordering of the prompts is the best ordering, but I would rather see the prompt be broken down into two because having to do so much just for one questions seems too tedious.

Q49: I think it may be helpful to break up the prompts? Such as: / - What is something that seems wrong in each of these code examples? / Then if the student still doesn't answer, then follow up with: / - What is something that is correct in each of these code examples? /  /  / I'm not sure if this would actually help? But how I feel about the prompts is that when you ask the student to answer both right and wrong about each of the prompts it can seem overwhelming to do, especially for a m/c question that isn't necessarily supposed to take a long time. However, it is important to think about these questions when a student is in the learning process, so that is why I broke up the one prompt into two prompts. The first question gets the student narrow down the choices.  The second question asks the student is the code example doing what it is supposed to be doing? /  / I'm not sure if the ordering of the prompts is the best ordering, but I would rather see the prompt be broken down into two because having to do so much just for one questions seems too tedious.

How do you quantify how well someone learns something? One exception is the "one great way to learn more is to stop and think!" prompt. / That prompt is worse than useless - it is annoying... / It takes my attention away from the course material and that is not productive. /  / Talk about "learning more" is vague and pointless. How do you quantify how well someone learns something? If it's volume, then those students who just memorize their way through class are the smartest people around (which we know is far from the truth). If it's quality, then you can't even put that into words to begin with, so why bother? / I think your attention is in the wrong place when you start off asking a question like that... /  / Taking a pause to think about what led a student to their answer is indeed a good prompt to give, it just needs to be worded in a more specific, useful, and deliberate way.
